<div class="line-numbers" aria-hidden="true" style="counter-reset:line-number 0"><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div><div class="line-number"></div></div></div><p>Autowiring means: Spring automatically finds the required bean from the IoC container and injects it into another bean, instead of manually creating dependencies.</p>
<p>How Autowiring Works:</p>
<ol>
<li>Scan classes annotated with @Component, @Service, @Repository, @Controller, etc.</li>
<li>Register them as bean definitions.</li>
<li>Create bean instances.</li>
<li>Inspect constructors, fields, and methods that need dependencies.</li>
<li>Search the ApplicationContext for matching beans.</li>
<li>Inject the selected beans.</li>
<li>Manage the bean lifecycle.</li>
</ol>
<h3 id="multi-bean-injection" tabindex="-1"><a class="header-anchor" href="#multi-bean-injection"><span>Multi-bean Injection</span></a></h3>
<p>Spring has default rules for multi-bean injection. The general rule is:</p>
<p>If you inject an array, collection, or Map, Spring finds all beans whose type matches the declared element/value type and injects them together. For Map, the key must be String, and Spring uses the bean name as the key.</p>
